    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-12-23T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-12-23T19:00:00-05:00" n="488"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d488">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">824.50/294: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Bolwia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Boal</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">La Paz</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-12-23T20:00:00-04:00"
                            >December 23, 1943—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 24—3:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2013. For Assistant Secretary Berle. Please telegraph for my own information what
                    the situation is with regard to Bolivian funds and Government monetary reserves
                    in the United States. Are they <pb facs="0550" n="538" xml:id="pg_538"/>
                    blocked? Development Corporation has about 3 million dollars in the Banco
                    Central which comes from former Bolivian Government deposit. You may wish to see
                    whether Export-Import Bank desires to instruct its directors in La Paz including
                        Egger<note n="14" xml:id="d488fn14">Rowland A. Egger, Manager, Bolivian
                        Development Corporation.</note> against any withdrawals either in Bolivia or
                    in the United States in excess of regular running expenses. While Inslee<note
                        n="15" xml:id="d488fn15">Joseph A. Inslee, Representative of the
                        Export-Import Bank.</note> has some fears regarding this as a precedent for
                    the Bolivian side both Egger and Crespo<note n="16" xml:id="d488fn16">Alberto
                        Crespo Gutierrez, President of the Bolivian Development Corporation and
                        former Minister of National Economy.</note> feel this would be very
                    desirable if done immediately.</p>
                <p>In view of Crespo’s arrest and later release today “because his cooperation would
                    be needed” Egger and I fear the Junta might seek to put pressure on the
                    directors to use their present powers by threatening the welfare Crespo and his
                    family.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Boal</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
